## Placeholders in Strings :
Placeholders allow inserting variable values dynamically into strings.

1. Old Placeholder Style (% Formatting) :
Borrowed from C language formatting.
| Placeholder | Type    |
| ----------- | ------- |
| `%s`        | String  |
| `%d`        | Integer |
| `%f`        | Float   |

Example 1 : 
sentence = "%s %s was the president of USA"
print(sentence % ("Barack", "Obama"))
Output :
Barack Obama was the president of USA

Example 2 : 
sentence = "%s is %d years old"
print(sentence % ("Kiruba", 23))
Output :
Kiruba is 23 years old

2. .format() Method (Python 3+)
More flexible than % formatting.
Example 1 — Without Index
name = "Kiruba"
age = 23
print("My name is {} and I am {} years old".format(name, age))
Output : 
My name is Kiruba  and I am 23 years old

Example 2 — With Index
name = "Kiruba"
age = 23
print("My name is {0} and I am {1} years old".format(name, age))
Output :
My name is Kiruba  and I am 23 years old

Example 3 — With Named Arguments 
name = "Kiruba"
age = 23
print("My name is {name} and I am {age} years old".format(name=name, age=age))
Output : 
My name is Kiruba  and I am 23 years old

3. Format Strings (f-Strings)
Modern placeholder style introduced in Python 3.6+.
Syntax :
f"Text {variable}"
Example 1 : 
name = "Charlz"
print(f"Hello, {name}")
Output :
Hello, Charlz

Example 2
x = 10
y = 20
print(f"The sum of x + y is {x + y}")
Output :
The sum of x + y is 30

## Why f-Strings are Preferred
=> More readable and clean
=> Faster than % and .format()
=> Values evaluated directly at runtime
=> Supports expressions inside {}

## Real-World Usage
=> Logging and debugging
=> Application messages
=> API responses
=> Backend services
=> Reports and email generation
